I am running windows 10 with python version of 2.7.13. I'm using colorama for colored output along with the readline module for tab completion in raw_input(). So far the tab completer works. But when I call ```colorama.init()```, tab completion no longer works. The function is somehow interfering with the readline completer. I know both modules make use of the ctypes module so  there may be a problem in their. Here is my code 
```
import readline
import colorama

colorama.init()

COMMANDS = ['help','exit','show']
def complete(text, state):
    for cmd in COMMANDS:
        if cmd.startswith(text):
            if not state:
                return cmd
            else:
                state -= 1
def main_handler_console():
    readline.parse_and_bind("tab: complete")
    readline.set_completer(complete)
    while True:
        test_input=raw_input(':')
        print test_input
main_handler_console()
```
This is the simplified version of the code, I managed to isolate it down to this section where the ```colorama.init()``` is interfering with the tab completer. Commenting out ```colorama.init()``` makes the completer work.

        urls = list(self.gen_urls(text))
        return urls if not only_unique else list(set(urls))

The above has an issue in that it needlessly creates the initial list even when a set is desired. This can be wasteful of memory. I didn't realize this before, but a better form is:

        urls = self.gen_urls(text)
        urls = set(urls) if only_unique else urls
        return list(urls)

